# You Can Build Web Apps. Yes, You.

Maybe you're a designer who wants to bring your ideas to life. Maybe you're in marketing and tired of waiting for developers. Or maybe you're just curious about how apps are made.

Good news: you don't need a computer science degree. You don't need to understand everything before you start. You just need to follow along.

{% callout type="info" title="What We'll Do" %}
1. Download an app called **Cursor**
2. Use Cursor's AI assistant to set up everything else
3. Run your first code

That's it. The AI will guide you through any technical stuff.
{% /callout %}

---

# Step 1: Download Cursor

Cursor is like a smart notepad for code. It has an AI assistant built in that can help you write code, explain things, and even run commands for you.

{% card title="Download Cursor" variant="feature" %}
1. Go to [cursor.com](https://cursor.com)
2. Click the download button
3. Install it like any other app (drag to Applications on Mac, or run the installer on Windows)
4. Open Cursor
{% /card %}

When you first open Cursor, it might ask you to sign in or create an account. Follow the prompts—it only takes a minute.

---

# Step 2: Meet Your AI Assistant

Once Cursor is open, you'll see a code editor. Don't worry about all the buttons and menus for now.

**Press `Cmd + I` on Mac or `Ctrl + I` on Windows.**

This opens the AI chat. This is your new best friend. You can ask it anything, and it will help you.

{% callout type="tip" title="How This Works" %}
From now on, we'll give you **prompts** to copy and paste into this AI chat. The AI will explain what's happening and run the commands for you. You don't need to memorize anything.
{% /callout %}

---

# Step 3: Let the AI Check Your Computer

Before we install anything, let's see what you already have. Copy this entire prompt and paste it into the Cursor AI chat:

{% card title="Prompt 1: Check My System" variant="feature" %}
```
I'm a complete beginner setting up my computer for web development. I've never used a terminal before.

Please help me check what's already installed on my computer. Run the necessary commands and explain the results in simple terms.

Check for:
1. What operating system I'm using
2. If Node.js is installed (and what version)
3. If NVM is installed
4. If Git is installed

After checking, tell me what we need to install next. Keep your explanation simple - imagine you're talking to someone who has never written code before.
```
{% /card %}

The AI will run some commands and show you the results. Read what it says—it will tell you what's next.

---

# Step 4: Install NVM (Your Version Manager)

NVM is a tool that installs and manages Node.js (which you need to run web applications). Don't worry about what that means yet—just copy this prompt:

{% card title="Prompt 2: Install NVM" variant="feature" %}
```
I need to install NVM (Node Version Manager) on my computer. I'm a complete beginner.

Please:
1. Detect my operating system
2. Give me the exact steps to install NVM
3. If there are commands to run, explain what each one does in plain English before running it
4. After installation, verify it worked

If I'm on Windows, walk me through downloading and installing NVM for Windows step by step.

If I'm on Mac, check if I have Homebrew first. If not, help me install that first.

If I'm on Linux, use the curl installation script.

Go slow and check with me before each major step.
```
{% /card %}

{% callout type="info" title="This Might Take a Few Minutes" %}
The AI might need to install other tools first (like Homebrew on Mac). That's normal. Just follow along with what it tells you.
{% /callout %}

---

# Step 5: Install Node.js

Now that NVM is installed, we can use it to install Node.js. This is what actually runs your web applications.

{% card title="Prompt 3: Install Node.js" variant="feature" %}
```
NVM should now be installed on my computer. Please help me:

1. First, verify that NVM is working (if it's not, help me troubleshoot)
2. Install the latest LTS (stable) version of Node.js using NVM
3. Verify that Node.js and npm are now installed
4. Explain in simple terms what we just installed and why it matters

Remember, I'm a beginner. If something goes wrong, help me fix it step by step.
```
{% /card %}

---

# Step 6: Create Your First Project

You now have everything you need! Let's create a simple project to make sure it all works.

{% card title="Prompt 4: Create My First Project" variant="feature" %}
```
I want to create my very first web project to test that everything is working.

Please help me:
1. Create a new folder for my project (call it "my-first-app")
2. Set it up as a web project
3. Create a simple file that prints "Hello World!"
4. Run it and show me the result

Explain each step as we go. I want to understand what's happening, not just copy commands.

After it works, suggest one small thing I can change to see how the code works.
```
{% /card %}

{% callout type="success" title="Congratulations!" %}
If you see "Hello World!" in your terminal, you did it! You just ran your first code. Everything from here is just building on what you've learned.
{% /callout %}

